column1: 115018;instagram;2018-12-12 19:22:54;FALSE;"my grandmother found my first white hair when i was 19! more quickly came.

i spent my 20‚Äôs adding highlights to mix in the white & grays. by 30 my hair was at least 30% gray/white. i switched to full colourings with a lovely shade of red that i loved. i also switched to natural colour options that aligned with my values. aveda has been my go-to for nearly 5 years now.
i often received compliments on my ‚Äònatural‚Äô red. i always laughed
column3: and i wish it was natural. my original colour is a dark brown.. i haven‚Äôt seen it in years - mostly because of the gray.

column1: doctors said it must be in my genes. my parents both had early gray
column2: but not nearly as much as me. i actually have more gray/white than my mom does! maybe as much as my dad. they are 20 years older!

column1: i‚Äôve been toying with letting it grow out for a couple years. three days after i returned from my big trip this fall
column2: i looked in the mirror and realized i‚Äôm ready. i thought i was a few years away

column1: much inner work led me to understand it stems from long held trauma & stress. i‚Äôm grateful i‚Äôve released most of it. it‚Äôs been an intense journey; and worth it. the transformation i‚Äôve been through this year in particular has really brought me home within myself. it‚Äôs showing beautifully in every area of my life. including acceptance of myself in all ways
column3: and real excitement for this journey!

column1: 115509;instagram;2018-12-12 14:29:26;TRUE;;"i was invited to speak to some set of teenagers over the weekend
column2: over the night i was praying for direction on what to talk about
column4: as i got in i asked them to bring out their writing¬† pads
column5: i asked just 1 question have you ever been sexually assaulted or molested by family members (nuclear or extended)i was shocked¬† at their answers
column6: after speaking i spoke with those who said yes privately
column7: they all had something in common
column8: they couldn't talk with their parents
column9: they were afraid they were not going to believe them or that they would be blamed or judged.i cried when i got home.as parents or even elder siblings we are so wrapped up in ourselves that we fail to see things going wrong around us
column10: we fail to see the signs!over the weekend an 18year old boy committed suicide because he was raped by his own sisters and couldn't speak out
column11: this led to depression and ultimately he hated himself and then death..10 minutes a day is enough time to speak to your kids.never be too busy to listen.

column1: 115695;instagram;2018-12-12 12:17:14;FALSE;"turning 20 and completing another year in paris was one of the hardest years in my life. in despite to my privilege of living a comfortable life
column2: protected by elitism and the benefits of a pale skin tone
column3: blue eyes and privileged education; my heart broke and whilst eating one day with a friend

column1: i wept for the realization that human beings when confronted with the truths of the systematic injustice of this world

i've been in a dark place inside my mind.
i've been playing the victim of my past for too long
column2: my response to everything that the world gave me was negative and i lacked self-love.

column1: i made it hard to be around me and impossible to help me
column2: on the defence i always blamed something that has happened in the past or what possibly could happen in the future.

column1: i refused to be responsible of my own happiness and kept waiting the world to change around me instead of trying to change myself.

column2: i travelled all the way to other side of the world to solve my problems. i thought that australia would be the solution to my unhappiness.

column1: the beginning was truly amazing but like you can imagine
when i realised that even traveling couldn't make me happy i started questioning if life was worth living at all.
when i found myself in the deepest level of self-pity and hate i decided to try one last time before making the last call.
i started absorbing information of self improvement and learning about the importance of mindset. i did my best to change my thoughts everytime i found myself thinking negatively.
i made small changes step by step
column3: drinking less alcohol and eating better.

column1: slowly i started noticing my mind automatically turn into more positive way of thinking and my energy levels going up. unexpected opportunities started coming at me and i felt.. well.. somehow happy.
it was quite easy to keep doing these improvements when so quickly i could see how it changed my entire world. just by changing myself first.
making yourself a better human being is a journey that never ends.
we're all responsible for our own happiness
column2: no one else can't do it for you.

column1: if you chase for happiness you're gonna find yourself running like a headless chicken your whole life
column2: but if you choose to find happiness from this moment

column1: i'm glad to say i've never been this truly happy.

column3: it's because i choose to be.

column1: i have been in a dark place inside my mind.
i have been playing the victim of my past for too long
column2: my response to everything that the world gave me was negative and i lacked self-love.

column1: i made it hard to be around me and impossible to help me
column2: on the defence i always blamed something that has happened in the past or what possibly could happen in the future.

column1: i refused to be responsible of my own happiness and kept waiting the world to change around me instead of trying to change myself.

column2: i travelled all the way to other side of the world to solve my problems. i thought that australia would be the solution to my unhappiness.

column1: the beginning was truly amazing but like you can imagine
when i realised that even traveling couldn't make me happy i staed questioning if life was woh living at all.
when i found myself in the deepest level of self-pity and hate i decided to try one last time before making the last call.
i staed absorbing information of self improvement and learning about the impoance of mindset. i did my best to change my thoughts everytime i found myself thinking negatively.
i made small changes step by step
column3: drinking less alcohol and eating better.

column1: slowly i staed noticing my mind automatically turn into more positive way of thinking and my energy levels going up. unexpected oppounities staed coming at me and i felt.. well.. somehow happy.
it was quite easy to keep doing these improvements when so quickly i could see how it changed my entire world. just by changing myself first.
making yourself a better human being is a journey that never ends.
we're all responsible for our own happiness
column2: no one else can not do it for you.

column1: 115918;instagram;2018-12-12 07:40:16;FALSE;"what forms does disability discrimination take in the workplace?
the equality act protects employees from discrimination during every stage of employment from recruitment
the act also covers various forms of discrimination:
direct discrimination ‚Äì when an employee is treated unfairly due to their known disability.
discrimination by perception ‚Äì when an employee is treated unfairly because they are perceived to have a disability (regardless of whether or not they actually have that disability).
discrimination by association ‚Äì when an employee is treated unfairly because they are connected to someone with a disability
column2: for example those who are caring for a child or parent.

column1: indirect discrimination ‚Äì this relates to a change to or introduction of policies and procedures that unfairly disadvantage an employee with a disability.
harassment ‚Äì when an employee with a disability is subjected to unwanted and inappropriate behaviour that causes distress

column1: 115920;instagram;2018-12-12 07:42:34;FALSE;"i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.
steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences?
abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit the hijacked party of puppets is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are just helpless with the fake content - there is no way they are going to risk their business by taking a real responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.
trump is truly playing along with his tweets

the bigger issue still is that republicans willingly piggybacked this lunacy while campaigning for the midterms and keep abusing the faith of their fellow men. this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.
